Exercise 1¶

  • Ladislaus Josephovich Bortkiewicz was a Russian economist and statistician. He noted that the Poisson distribution can be very useful in applied statistics when describing low-frequency events in a large population. In a famous example he showed that the number of deaths by horse kick among the Prussian army follows the Poisson distribution.
  • Considering the following two sets of observations taken over a fixed large time interval in two different corps:
$y$ death soldiers 0 1 2 3 4 $\geq$ 5
$n_1$ observations 109 65 22 3 1 0
$n_2$ observations 144 91 32 11 2 0

1. assuming a uniform prior, compute and plot the posterior distribution for $\lambda$, the death rate over the measurement time. Determine the posterior mean, median and variance, and compute the 95 % credibility interval.¶

Useful functions¶
In [ ]:
# function to find the mean of the distributions
find_mean <- function(lambda, alpha, mu){
    mean <- integrate(function(lambda) dgamma(lambda, alpha, mu) * lambda, 0.1, 1.1)
    return(mean)
}
In [ ]:
# function to find the cdf
find_cum <- function(f){
    cum <- rep(0, length(f))
    for(i in 2:length(f)){
     cum[i] <- cum[i-1] + f[i]/n 
    }
    return(cum)
}
In [ ]:
# function to find the median
find_median <- function(f, cumn){
    for(i in 1:length(f)){
        if(cumn[i] > 0.5){
            break()
        }
    }
    return(lambda[i])
}
In [ ]:
# function to find the variance 
find_var <- function(alpha, mean, mu){
    E2 <- integrate(function(lambda) dgamma(lambda, alpha, mu) * lambda^2, 0.1, 1.1)
    var <- E2$value - mean$value^2
    return(var)
}
In [ ]:
# function to find the credibility interval
find_interval <- function(cumn, percentage){
    for(i in 1: length(cumn)){
        if(cumn[i] > percentage){
            break
        }
    }
    return(lambda[i])
}

Assuming the measurements as independent, the likelihood for each of the two observations becomes $$ f(\{y_i\}|\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} f(y_i|\lambda) \propto \lambda^{\sum_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} y_i} e^{-n_{obs}\lambda} $$ This is proportional to a Gamma distribution $Gamma(\lambda|\alpha, \mu)$ with $$ \alpha = \sum_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} y_i + 1 \qquad \text{and} \qquad \mu = n_{obs} $$

In [ ]:
mu1 <- length(y1)
mu2 <- length(y2)

# compute the likelihood for the first observation
alpha1 <- sum(y1) + 1
likel1 <- dgamma(lambda, alpha1, mu1)

# compute the likelihood fo the second observation
alpha2 <- sum(y2) +1
likel2 <- dgamma(lambda, alpha2, mu2)

Since we assumed an uniform prior for $\lambda$, the posterior distribution is proportional to the prior $$ P(\lambda|\{y_i\}) \propto f(\{y_i\}|\lambda) $$

# normalized posteriors
post1 <- likel1
post2 <- likel2

2. assuming now a Jeffreys’ prior, $$ g(\lambda) \propto \frac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda}} \qquad \text{, with} \quad \lambda > 0 $$ compute and plot the posterior distribution for $\lambda$, the death rate over the measurement time. Determine the posterior mean, median and variance, and compute the 95% credibility interval.¶

Assuming now a Jeffrey's prior, the posterior is $$ P(\lambda|\{y_i\}) \propto f(\{y_i\}|\lambda) \times g(\lambda)$$ This is proportional to a Gamma distribution $Gamma(\lambda|\beta, \mu)$ with $$ \beta = \sum_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} y_i + \frac{1}{2} \qquad \text{and} \qquad \mu = n_{obs} $$

In [ ]:
beta1 <- sum(y1) + 1./2.
beta2 <- sum(y2) + 1./2.
In [ ]:
prior_jeff <- function(lambda){
    g <- 1/sqrt(lambda)
    return(g)
}
In [ ]:
# compute the posteriors
post1_jeff <- dgamma(lambda, beta1, mu1)
post2_jeff <- dgamma(lambda, beta2, mu2)

Exercise 2¶

Solve Exercise 1 with a Markov Chain Monte Carlo. Build your own MCMC, using the functions introduced during lectures, or using a MCM library like JAGS.¶

I will now solve the problem building my own MCMC

The two posteriors are:

  • $P(\lambda|\{y_i\}) \propto Gamma(\lambda|\alpha, \mu)$ with $$ \alpha = \sum_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} y_i + 1 \qquad \text{and} \qquad \mu = n_{obs} $$ using the uniform prior
  • $P(\lambda|\{y_i\}) \propto Gamma(\lambda|\beta, \mu)$ with $$ \beta = \sum_{i=1}^{n_{obs}} y_i + \frac{1}{2} \qquad \text{and} \qquad \mu = n_{obs} $$ using the Jeffrey's prior
In [ ]:
# vector with the number of observations of each set
n_obs <- c(length(y1), length(y2))
mu <- n_obs

alpha <- c(sum(y1)+1, sum(y2)+1)
beta <- c(sum(y1)+0.5, sum(y2)+0.5)
In [ ]:
# test functions
unif_post <- function(lambda){
    f_unif <- dgamma(lambda, alpha, mu)
    return(f_unif)
}

jeff_post <- function(lambda){
    f_jeff <- dgamma(lambda, beta, mu)
    return(f_jeff)
}
In [ ]:
# MCMC metripolis code
metropolis <- function(func, theta_init, n_samples, sigma, index){
    theta_now <- theta_init
    func_now <- func(theta_now)[index]
    func_samples <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = n_samples, ncol = 2)
    accepted <- 0

    for(i in 1:n_samples){
        theta_prop <- rnorm(1, theta_now, sigma)
        func_prop <- func(theta_prop)[index]
        rho <- func_prop/func_now

        # update
        if(rho >= 1 || rho > runif(1)){
            theta_now <- theta_prop
            func_now <- func_prop
            accepted <- accepted + 1
        }

        # store in the matrix
        func_samples[i, 1] <- func_now
        func_samples[i, 2] <- theta_now
    }

    rate <- accepted/n_samples
    cat(paste("The acceptance rate is: ", rate*100, "% \n"))
    
    return(func_samples)
}
